The above code uses a priority queue to record nodes and their corresponding minimum distances, and the queue is ordered by priority. At the beginning, the queue is set to node 1 with priority 0.  The algorithm is iterative.  At each iteration, the top priority of the queue (cur) and its priority (cost) are taken out of the queue.  In the process of getting rid of (cost) the next vertex with a lower priority is added.  At the end, the next closest neighbor is not necessarily the goal.  Therefore, after the traversal is completed, it needs to be verified whether the end point is reached.

It should be noted that the code only processes the distances of each vertex in the priority queue.  Although there may be more than one path with the same distance, only the first path will be traversed.

The code has a time complexity of O (mn log n) and a space complexity of O (n + m).


